[Report by World Bank]

16 Apr 2015 W. Africa: Ebola researchers take new look at risk of sexual transmission
http://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/17/world/africa/ebola-researchers-take-new-look-at-risk-of-sexual-transmission.html
[Medical investigators are focused on 2 women who died of Ebola in March 2015 -- 1 in Liberia and 1 in Sierra Leone. There were no known risk factors. However, their male partners had survived Ebola in 2014, suggesting that the virus could be active in semen longer than researchers had previously believed, and that it was transmissible through sexual activity. Recently American and Liberian scientists have found genomic evidence which may support sexual contact as the cause of the Liberian case]
[The confirmation of sexual transmission of Ebola in these cases may be resolved by genetic homogeneity between the viral genomes from the women and their respective partners. Sexual transmission of Ebola virus has been suggested by circumstantial evidence, but never with 100 percent certainty. Because the testes are protected from antibody, the virus could possibly replicate there beyond the viremic phase, and be transmitted without being neutralized by antibody. It is important to follow-up on these cases to determine the probability of sexual transmission so that there is better understanding of the risk factors for Ebola transmission. But most likely sexual transmission is a rare event that can be observed during large outbreaks. Thorough epidemiologic studies and genetic analyses should clarify this 1 way or the other, but because of the sensitivity of the topic, this will no doubt be difficult. - Mod.LK]

16 Apr 2015 International: team begins field trials for solar-powered 'suitcase lab,' Ebola assay
https://www.genomeweb.com/pcr/international-team-begins-field-trials-solar-powered-suitcase-lab-ebola-assay
[It is based on isothermal recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA) chemistry from UK firm TwistDx, a subsidiary of Alere]

18 Apr 2015 Kenya: Initial results of Ebola vaccine [rVSV-ZEBOV] trials in Kenya show it is safe
http://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/Initial-results-of-Ebola-vaccine-trials-in-Kenya-show-it-is-safe/-/2558/2690326/-/3u623yz/-/index.html
[Phase I trial was of 138 volunteer nurses and clinicians across 4 sites in Kilifi, on Kenya's coast. There were no serious side effects, although some experienced transient joint pain and/or joint swelling and some experienced fever in the 1st few days. Switzerland and Germany also participated in the trial]

